Food to blame for European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation measured in the eurozone is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the euro area, the inflation rate was higher than expected in November - after the 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg reported.
Official forecasts are only 3%, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the Leitzins. In its discretion, the interest rate cut would favour rising commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment the emergence of an inflation spiral.
The ECB strives to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the throes: inflation must be “correlated” in order to rule out the need for action later on.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a twelve-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the eurozone is due to rising food and energy prices.
MATIF wheat quotations rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans has also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose 52 percent this year - last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but it is expected to fall to 1.9% in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
The Gallup Government Crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz sympathizers has grown considerably until the beginning of December, with the party having the largest base camp for the first time since 2002, while approval for the socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference among the party-loyal voters is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to one-fifth (20 percent) of approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary entry threshold: they come to two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low, the general economic mood has continued to deteriorate - never before has the proportion of those who judge the country's economic situation as "extremely bad" been so high (41 percent), while a further 46 percent consider it "pretty bad".
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families once again see the change in their financial situation as more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects the situation to deteriorate further; only one-tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents – a historic high – considered the Prime Minister’s work “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence generally in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while the proportion of proponents for Viktor Orbán accounts for 38 percent.
Around 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared with 27% distrust of the leader of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of the political mood is the number of those who think that one could get the dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister even without changing government.
After the riots last October, if 35% were still in favour of the government and the head of government, that share today is only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent responded that they would “participate with certainty,” and another 20% would “probably” cast their vote.
By comparison, if parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would go to the polls "with certainty" and another 15 percent would consider their participation "probable".
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital daily fee.
Relocated to the group of participants in the referendum "with certainty", the proportion of opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be 81, 84 and 89 percent, respectively.
