In many places, disinfectants are saved
Today, more than a thousand infections have been registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to curbing the infections, according to the senior doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, there was a similar infection.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital, but a short time later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. An important operation could not be performed since then because of the bacteria that is still in the patient’s body.
By December 10, 1094 multi-resistant infections were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to the lead doctor of the National Epidemiology Center, Karolina Böröcz.
So many infections triggered by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about one-third of people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, tonsil inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria are produced from the well-responsive bacteria, which spread rapidly in the hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Particularly in patients with weakened or permanently malfunctioning immune systems, but also in elderly or low-weight patients, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, the MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday life in the hospital.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
“Such patients are isolated, nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks during care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
While patients are being examined for MRSA when they are admitted to the hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is too rare
The majority of MRSA-induced infections in hospitals would be preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for curbing the development or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and retirement homes, hospitals should examine the admitted patients and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no state health insurance grants for this investigation.
Most cases therefore only come to light when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases in Hungary.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even rarer, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Saved on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by nursing staff.
This is precisely why hand washing or wearing gloves and masks is very important, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in domestic hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient.
The rooms are often overcrowded, the beds lined up tightly, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, it unfortunately even happens in the financially less well-off hospitals that disinfectants are saved, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that almost favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina Böröcz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting to grips with MRSA infections causes huge costs to health insurance companies, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
After initial signs, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared preventing the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and preventing infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
