A further EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three loan agreements totalling EUR 400 million on Friday in Budapest.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million framework for the financing of transport and environmental projects implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund. The loan agreement of EUR 100 million has been signed earlier.
The amount of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be spent on the budgetary financing of educational projects.
The EIB has granted a total of EUR 300 million to Hungary for this purpose; the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be decided later in the context of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the area of innovation, the contracting parties have signed an agreement of EUR 50 million, which will mainly be used for research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
At the meeting, the subway line 4 was also mentioned.
It was agreed that once Hungary has clarified the details of subway financing with the EU, the original contract and possible modifications will be re-discussed.
According to János Veres, this would be possible in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects totalling EUR 8.4 billion in Hungary.
The loan interest rates are EURIBOR-bound, the loan is provided by the EIB with a deferment of 8 years, free of charge.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe looks at the formerly rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who is still buying the cheapest market in the EU, but which is becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently undoubtedly the most sought-after pavement for real estate purchases in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, by the sea are Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the Renner, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik are also in increasing demand.
According to estimates by Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the interior will also attract investors, for example Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the very favourable area of Russians is showing more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers enticing offers - commercial and office spaces offer highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its best track to become one of the most attractive European golfer’s paradises, attracting tourists in addition to the summer and winter seasons as well as the other two seasons.
Forward-looking investors are already buying in a large-scale fashion, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also seeking a change in their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are predominantly Russian buyers in the Black Sea and ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle buy either revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or abandoned houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connections and accessibility as well as communication opportunities are important, but also the proximity to a big city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed in the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of increasing value in the medium to long term.
Real estate in the capital, however, is constantly becoming more expensive, due to the ever-increasing demand.
In the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the past five years there has been an annual increase of 21 percent.
The price of real estate far exceeds the increase in salaries.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percent
Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced that the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out the emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate between developed and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are willing to support the developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on aid to developing countries was also reached.
The Adaptation Fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member council, expected to be held by the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as stated in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6%
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that by 2020, the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (measured by the 1990 levels), whether or not the "Agreement after 2012" will be achieved successfully, and the Union would even be willing to commit to a 30% reduction if other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to fulfil their commitments to the best of their ability and responsibly.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU, with its then 15 member states, had already committed itself to a decrease of 8%.
The target for Hungary is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will certainly meet, as can be seen in the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction plan set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international Nobel Peace Prize-winning scientific climate change committee of the UN in its latest report.
This would delay emission reduction, and increasing the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2°C would be unavoidable, with extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
British Army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British army have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan for the purpose of increasing popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube by itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The shots shot with miniature cameras mounted on helmets are controlled at the Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message unavoidable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such shots, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defense was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Commonwealth Office and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign deployments.
Such propaganda is almost free compared to traditional television advertising, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, as they confirm the existence of the military measures adopted by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots, which, in addition to the carefully edited, censored shots, also make it on the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films talk about the losses at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, numerous videos filmed in use have already been uploaded to the platform from the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre" for themselves.
The Americans, however, advertise in the slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less lifelike simulation.
