More and more forces mobilized for giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Trade Union Federation will form their coordination committee on Friday for the indefinite strike beginning on Monday.
On Saturday, a large protest assembly is held, on Monday - on the day of the referendum on the Health Insurance Act - the work stoppage begins.
Strike-related, significant traffic constraints are expected, as rail traffic is almost completely stopped, and the Budapest public transport companies (BKV) are also on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of Monday’s strike will be jointly announced by the League of Trade Unions and the Trade Union Federation on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA - MOSZ strike committee is also set up, which is responsible for coordinating the actions on Monday.
A large protest assembly will be held on Saturday, and as of Monday, all organizations that joined the strike will resign for an indefinite period of time unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike beginning on the day of the parliamentary vote on the Health Insurance Act was not defined.
If the National Council does not accept the Health Insurance Act, the trade unions immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees meet to discuss how to proceed.
Due to the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that a vote on the health insurance law will be held only in the later evening hours, or even at midnight.
The strikes starting on Monday will result in significant traffic constraints: the railway workers are laying down their work for an indefinite period of time, in the morning the majority of public transport and more than half of Volán companies are stationary.
At the same time, there will be roadblocks in one direction in many places.
Numerous trade unions and civil organizations have followed the call for strikes - the list of participants is constantly updated on the league website.
Some organizations announced strikes indefinitely, while others are planning a temporary shutdown.
Until Thursday afternoon, no agreement on sufficient services could be reached between the Hungarian Railway MV and the Free Trade Union of the railways VDSZSZ, although more and more people are travelling by train around the Christmas holidays.
According to previous reports, the BKV will strike between 7 and 9 a.m. at Budapest Airport, the LIGA unions for electricity and heat energy will lay down the work for four hours, and the Teachers’ Union, for example, the Democratic Teachers’ Union, have called for 2- and 2-8-hour strikes, respectively.
The Hungarian Medical Association alternately strikes nationwide at various times, the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organisation of the SZEF, the Forum for Trade Union Cooperation, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the league is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and present a new concept for social discourse.
The second demand concerns the gradual introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due from next year.
Requirement number three is that the eligible professional groups will have access to the early retirement system before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which belongs to the League of Trade Unions, did not accept the offer submitted by the Ministry of Transport concerning the sidelines and now calls for a new concept.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Increases State Risk
According to Political Capital’s Risk Analysis Division, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded this August with the support of the “Movement for a Better Hungary”, have increased the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's "Risk Warning Report" states, among other things, that in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the highest political risk is the "strengthening of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsies and non-Gypsies population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is presumably aimed at provoking such a dispute, according to the research institute.
As reported, this is seen as a failure on the part of political leaders: "Public people have left the discussion of the Roma question to representatives of radical political groups who have now built their political strategy on the Roma-Hungary opposition".
It is assumed that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favor extremities, and increase the likelihood of violent confrontations.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least thanks to the enormous attention from the domestic and foreign media, “have seriously damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity.”
We remember that since autumn 2006, the reorganization of radical and extremely right-wing groups in Hungary has been on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called "national self-defense associations" have been established.
“These groups have in common that they each define themselves as a civilian organization, while they openly brag about preparing their members for – sometimes armed – defense tasks (disaster protection, national defense, law enforcement), citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, or the state itself,” it said.
And further: all this is done according to that method which tries to disguise various political aspirations based on the political and party dissatisfaction of the population as a bourgeois initiative.
The emphasis on civil character and the form of association therefore serve not only to circumvent legal hurdles that could arise in the course of registration in court - it is also a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-increasing factor in relations with neighbouring countries.
“In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited as a potential source of danger in several neighbouring countries, according to some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries, in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of its own anti-Hungarian policy.
All of this has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he said.
From the research institute’s point of view, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not a single phenomenon in Central-East Europe, so the political risk for the entire region has grown.
As reported, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
In the background of the creation of the Bulgarian Guard were the Roma mass riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took the incidents as an opportunity to establish the National Guard, arguing that the organization’s goal is “national protection”.
In their opinion, a real "gypsy terror" has been felt in Bulgaria over the past 17 years, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent - according to Political Capital.
The initiative would have triggered a fierce debate in the Bulgarian public.
As I said, the increased risk of ethnic conflict is also evidenced by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced that they will set up their own guards for resistance purposes.
