Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of re-disposing the working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year brings us fewer such days.
Also in the EU and in America, something else is understood by "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between state holidays and non-working days.
Work-free days are usually church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the latter alone so that the New Year's celebrations can rest.
We have a total of 14 holidays throughout the year.
The national holidays are March 15 which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and October 23, the commemoration day of the revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the founding of the state, on the 1st of May the work, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “working day shift” has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is to be finalised, has been determined by the Minister of Labour in its own regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees, public employees and public service officials.
Excluded are only companies and facilities in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays.
This year, the working order is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in this country remains formal, as most take the time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or take the specially cancelled vacation.
Next year will have more holidays in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer re-dispositions on the working days than this year.
The calendar is first “turned upside down” around the day of work so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26th, will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd, can be a rest day.
The second redisposition is related to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th, you will have to process the Friday, October 24th in advance.
However, the end of the year will be completely marked by the holidays, after December 24th everything will lie and stop, even if New Year’s Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six Deterrent Little Things to Angry Workmates
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: They bring "color" to everyday life in the workplace.
The only question is whether you get used to these little inconveniences, or you better face the challenge and try to avoid these unintelligible, annoying situations.
Tips.
“Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called you,” a colleague says.
Did you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make up for it by perhaps calling the marketing department and confessing repentantly that you forgot to align the message (this is the less common method).
Usually, the thing is done with an apology.
Before you get involved in embarrassing excuses, consider how you can really give your colleagues unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrowing something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more nervous than reaching for a document, office accessories, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without questions, you should not borrow from your colleagues, because they are rightly upset when they find that something has gone away.
So, don't put envelopes or post-it out of the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more there when you urgently need it.
Talk about the private life of your colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop a gossip that has already been put into the world.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
One should not bind the information (or assumptions) about the private life of the colleagues to everyone's nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and reveals his inner secret to us, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, rather than aligning the person who is not present, even if others know about the problems of the colleague.
Sickly reported for no reason?
When you call in the office to report sick, citing tormenting headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable right now, or just want to rest, you should be clear about one thing: your own work, unstoppable tasks, projects with fixed deadlines now have to be done by your colleagues instead of by yourself.
So don't be fooled by your colleagues!
If you know the day before that you won’t make it to the office the next day, or that something could get in between, why you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
Cumshot, Geek, Phone calls
One is just deepened in his work, but is suddenly disturbed by the loud gossip of the colleagues?
Unwanted to listen to a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard?
One should not annoy colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (that one leads over their heads), tramplement, constant scolding or nagging.
All of this can be very annoying, even if they are not currently immersed in a task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not finished on time, you have forgotten to send an important letter or important messages, you should not seek the blame of your own forgetfulness from others!
If possible, you should not be excused for the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes and apologize if others were affected!
The question of how to make up for the mistake, or make up for the missed one, is all too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training pants and slippers: Convenient for at home, but has lost nothing in the office!
Not even then should you dress so casually, if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
