All is well (?).
The hvg.hu asked Balázs Zságer.
hvg.hu: This new hit raises the question: To what extent is your music reserved for a certain layer?
Baláz's Zságer: The term "layer music" doesn't mean much to me.
In my opinion, there are two boxes in pop music, not mainstream and underground, or alternative and pop, but commercial and honest.
Even the so-called alternative or underground music can be shallow and insignificant, but they can also only be produced for sale, which turns them into commercial music.
A good pop number can also come from an honest motif.
The listener’s willingness to listen also works according to this principle, independent of languages and national borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference in the openness of the Hungarian and foreign audiences to your music?
B. Zs.: Abroad, especially west of us, pop music has a larger tradition.
Not only teenagers or Twens go to concerts, but also the older audience.
They follow the trends in pop music that happen around them much more attentively because they also consider them to be part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What role does the audience play in your work?
Does it matter who, where, how many listen to your music?
B. Zs.: Of course, it’s a good feeling to see more and more coming to our concerts.
We have never written for the market.
Music is not created for a purpose, but for a reason.
The role of the audience is usually felt at the concerts, where there is already a mutual interaction, but it is only in the intangible changes of the moment.
However, one thing I noticed: If you want to make it right for everyone, you are no longer interesting.
hvg.hu: How far do you want to follow the example of Yonderboi?
He is a soloist and has built his career in the West.
B. Zs.: We don’t really go his way, apart from trying to interpret this into our music again and again.
We see ourselves more as team players who rely on each other’s musical presence and let it unfold.
In the beginning, of course, comparisons of our work with that of Yonderboi were inevitable, as several of us came out of his band and took a different path.
hvg.hu: "Wings of Love" comes first in the charts of Mr2 Petáfi.
Many have only heard the name Zagar in connection with this number.
Was the opening deliberately staged with a somewhat more popular style towards a wider audience?
B. Zs.: We didn’t have any plans to write a hit that would then be used as a drawhorse for the album.
