Integration of Slovak students in British schools fails
In British schools, the number of children from countries in Eastern Europe is increasing, raising fears among locals about the further development of local schooling.
The integration of Eastern Europeans has hitherto encountered a number of obstacles.
British schools even find cases where disputes between immigrants and the children of the original inhabitants increase in violence.
The problem with the integration of children from Eastern Europe into British schools is well illustrated by the case of North Kent, where disputes between locals and Slovak immigrants are gradually increasing.
Disputes, harassment and robbery among students have spread to relationships between parents.
The situation has already developed so far that police in Chatham arrested a Slovak woman who had beaten a ten-year-old boy with an iron rod.
The accused defended himself by saying that the boy insulted her with racist insults.
Police also had to intervene after an attack by two minor girls on a Slovak immigrant.
The girls had allegedly made racist remarks to the man and stoned him.
“When we went home, a boy climbed on a bush and spit on us.
When I told him to stop, he threw apples and pears at us and then exposed his buttocks,” a mother of Slovak students told The Times.
Complaints come from both sides.
One of the locals even described the dispute with the immigrants from Eastern Europe as a struggle for survival.
The cases cited testify that the mood between locals and immigrants at British schools is becoming increasingly tense.
In the UK, there are 70,000 Slovaks who came here looking for a job.
Approximately 3,000 Slovak students attend British schools.
Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday, it will come true if you choose just the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and all inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and enchanting cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this in abundance.
Only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
And then came the American epoch.
The Hotel Nacional was built at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the heads of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the US (especially during the prohibition) was welcomed and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew, and cars were driving across the broad boulevards that were among the iconic symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought himself a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojimar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio, show business stars and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
Cocktails can be mixed at the bar at Hotel Nacional.
And the cult cars of the fifties still drive around in Havana today, because the once imported schigulis and fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and humid air.
Havana, in particular its oldest part, may have fallen heavily, nowhere in the vicinity can you find as many wonderful colonial sights as here.
Other places are being cleaned out, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings much-needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have been created not only in Havana, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holguin and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba offers yet another marrot that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauges to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see nice and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have long since been in the museum elsewhere.
Excursion destinations
The most important places do not let out the majority of visitors to Cuba.
There is no need to write about Varadero or Havana.
All that remains to be mentioned is that in the aforementioned estate of Hemingway there is a museum whose visit should not be missed by anyone who likes this writer.
The Vieste Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on limestone soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks rise steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which even weathered rocky areas are covered by thick vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city founded shortly after the Spaniards colonized the island.
Fame and wealth came to her from the trade of slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the pretty beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, heavily influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed for four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is such a remote place that there was no road there in the fifties of the last century that would have connected the area to the rest of the country.
This isolation contributed to it being ignored.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth seeing interesting places in the area, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la Musica, which revives after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until morning.
Baracoa
This town in the east of Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads that lead from Guantanamo have to cross high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape barely touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was included by UNESCO in its World Heritage Directory thanks to its unspoilt nature.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in reality it was created about a hundred years after the trips of Columbus), and from the hill, where the former castle, the current Hotel El Castillo, stands, there are several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the best known.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra-Maestra Mountains, the bay of pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion that the descendants of slaves profess, about all this you could write many pages.
But, as they say, it’s better to look with your own eyes.
Allies in Afghanistan are passive, Americans claim.
Too few soldiers and the lack of necessary equipment, according to the United States, affect the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
NATO should, in the words of Defense Secretary Robert Gates, draw up a concrete plan for the next few years.
The mission in Afghanistan did not go according to their ideas, and the representatives of the countries that have stationed units in the south of the country agreed on this in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to the growing resistance on the part of the Taliban, the eight participating states are also discussing further coordination plans among the allies.
While the United States, through its defense minister Robert Gates, called on NATO units to increase activity, Britain sees the priority in strengthening the authority of the Afghan government and in intensifying development aid.
“Afghanistan is experiencing progress, but military power can only be part of the solution.
Another part is allowing residents to start developing their own economy and security,” Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The Afghan insurgents’ activity has reached the highest level in five years, according to the U.S. Army.
The number of violence has increased by 27 percent compared to the previous year, in the southern province of Helmand even by sixty percent.
NATO countries have deployed about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, about a quarter of them in the southern territory.
According to the United States, however, the allies have reached an absolute limit in terms of the organization and equipment of the units.
Specifically, they are calling for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train the Afghan units.
“We will have to seriously think about the concrete goals for the next time and the way we can achieve them,” Gates said.
The same was said today by NATO Secretary-General Jaap de Hoop.
“I am not pleased with what we have on land and in the air in Afghanistan.
We have about ninety percent of the soldiers and equipment we need, and that’s too little,” De Hoop told Reuters agency at the conclusion of three-day talks with the Japanese government in Tokyo.
Who is passive
Among the countries involved, there has also been a dispute over the last few months as to whether all the allies in Afghanistan are doing their best.
Germany, for example, has been criticized for its passivity.
“The Germans are relatively numerous in Afghanistan.
But they are stationed in areas where there is only a minimum of violence and the fighting requirements for them are not as high as for us in the southern and eastern part of the country,” Gates said.
The British tabloid "Sun" this week referred to the German soldiers as lazy.
"Afghan Non-Supreme Uncovers: The Germans are making games while our boys are fighting," the Sun wrote in a post supplemented by photos of German soldiers playing table tennis.
The German newspaper went over to counter-attack and printed a picture of a British unit in a rugby competition in the southern part of Afghanistan.
Government debt will rise to one trillion in 2009
Each Czech has a national debt of 84000 kroner.
The total debt rose to 842.7 billion kroner by the end of September.
The government had planned to go into debt this year with 159.2 billion cones.
However, at the beginning of December, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion thanks to the better development of state budgetary policy.
The national debt of the Czech Republic rose to 842.7 billion kroner by the end of September.
In the first nine months of this year, they increased by 40.2 billion.
Since June, however, they have fallen by 13.4 billion.
The Treasury Department confirmed its data on the public debt from the beginning of October.
Each Czech owes 84000 crowns.
Over the past year, the state owed more than 111 billion kroner.
“Until now, it seems that thanks to the lower deficit for next year, we may not cross the trillion kroner limit until 2009.
Next year, debt should move between 900 billion and a trillion kroner,” said David Marek, analyst at Patria Finance, the server iHNed.cz.
Vladimir Pikora, analyst for Next Finance, said: “We could get over from a trillion in 2009.
When exactly depends on the next budget we don’t know yet.
If it turns out that the situation is changing on the political stage, and if politicians are willing to save more, it could take until 2010.
But I don’t expect such a change,” he noted.
Debt is Growing
The national debt comes from the debt of the state government and mainly from the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
The public debt is financed by treasury notes, government bonds, direct bonds or, for example, by bonds from the European Investment Bank.
Domestic debt has risen to 719.4 billion kroner this year.
The government’s foreign debt has now increased by 1.7 billion kroner to 123.3 billion.
The so-called marketable national debt reached 803.3 billion kroner at the end of September and fell by 13.7 billion since June.
The average maturity of government debt increased to 6.5 years.
Total debt increased 13 percent over the year from the first quarter to the third quarter, which is really a lot given how well the economy is doing.
It is interesting that the growth can be seen mainly in the debt securities, where the increase is 20 percent.
It’s bad that debt is rising, but on the other hand, it shows that you can do something even before the pension reform comes,” Pikora commented on the data.
Better than expected
The 2007 financing strategy and government debt management showed that the government had planned to take in 159.2 billion kroner this year.
However, at the beginning of December, the Ministry reduced the plan to 152.8 billion crowns, thanks to the better development of state budgetary policy.
This amount is mainly due to the government budget deficit, which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year instead of the estimated 91.3 billion.
It is also a maximum of 13.3 billion kroner for the consolidation agency, a 10 billion reserve to pay pensions, the financing of government bonds for 43 billion kroner and 1.8 billion kroner for bonds from the European Investment Bank.
For giving a name to a teddy bear, she was brought before a court in Khartoum today.
According to her lawyer, the British teacher, who had been accused of insulting Islam in Sudan, was sentenced to 15 days in prison and subsequently expulsion by a court in Khartoum on Thursday evening.
The British woman was accused of allowing six- to seven-year-old students to give a teddy bear the name of Mahomet, although any representation of the Islamic Prophet is prohibited.
She deserved to be whipped.
After parents of students complained several times to the Sudanese Ministry of Culture, the 54-year-old elementary school teacher, who worked at the Unity High School in Khartoum, was picked up at her home on Sunday and accused of insulting Islam under Article 125 of the Sudanese Criminal Code.
In fact, this matter begins in September, when the teacher asks her six- to seven-year-old students to choose a name for the class teddy.
The children suggest eight names, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed, reports school principal Robert Boules.
Finally, when the class votes, 20 out of 23 children choose Mohammed as their favorite first names.
Certainly, Muhammad is the name of the Islamic Prophet, but above all a very common first name in Sudan.
Then the children created a book for the class, with the photo of the bear on it and the caption My name is Mohammed.
The bear itself did not carry a sign with that name, but the problem is quite simple that the depiction of the Islamic Prophet is considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well, and she would never have done anything that could be too close to a religious belief, I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name, in his opinion this is just an innocent mistake.
A view that many students share with the teacher, which they describe as very attentive to their students and as a person who never talks about religion in the classroom.
Keep in mind that the first name Mohammed is also the second most frequently given name in the UK, for which 14 different spelling methods exist in English.
This name, often chosen by Muslim families, is considered a kind of veneration to the Prophet (it is often given to the firstborn of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this first name?
Can you give it to a toy, for example?
This is, of course, a matter of interpretation.
There was no agreement on the future status of the province at the last negotiating session in Vienna on Wednesday.
At the end of the failure
The Serbs and Albanians from Kosovo ended a sixth and final discussion on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome their controversies about the future status of the separatist province.
It is regrettable that the parties could not reach an agreement on the status, said European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region is at stake, its American counterpart Frank Wilsner urged Belgrade and Pristina to meet their commitments to maintain peace and continue the talks beyond the end of the negotiations.
No acts of violence are expected in the immediate future, but we are at the beginning of a very difficult time, he added, indicating that there are quite clear tensions.
End of conciliation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which unites the European Union, the US and Russia, will meet for the last time in Serbia and Kosovo on Monday.
The future of the 90% of Albanian-speaking province could become clearer if Ischinger, Wilsner and Russian intermediary Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The talks of Baden, near Vienna, constituted the sixth and last negotiating session since last August the troika had received the order from the UN for a new mediation.
Americans and Europeans expect their mediation mandate to end on December 10.
The Russians, who had already blocked Kosovo’s independence from the Security Council, insist on continuing negotiations beyond this end date.
Russia was and remains an advocate of a negotiated solution, a consensual solution, Botsane-Chartchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After having been under UN administration for eight years, the Western countries consider independence under EU supervision to be the only solution with a future.
Pristina is ready to unilaterally announce them if the Security Council should not decide in their favor.
Belgrade calls for greater autonomy
Unfortunately, no agreement could be reached, the president of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, announced at the hotel in Baden, where these negotiations have been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former leader of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, shared his regrets.
He added, however, that Belgrade’s proposed plan for autonomy belongs to a past that has led to murders and deportations.
Domino Effect
Serbian President Boris Tradic, for his part, felt that a compromise should always be sought, and warned the Albanian majority from Kosovo of the consequences of a unilateral declaration of independence of the province.
Belgrade believes that there is a “domino effect” in a region that has been weakened by the independence wars of the 1990s.
For Serbia, this does not mean that a compromise would be impossible, he said.
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision be made solely in the Security Council, where its Russian ally holds a veto.
The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word
Only one decision from the ranks of the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia, Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
These negotiations took two years.
They must end as they started: in the Security Council.
The journalists were told by Fatmir Sejdiu that Kosovo’s parliament would have the final say on the status, adding that any unilateral declaration of independence on the part of the Albanian-speaking population would proceed in coordination with the Western countries.
Bush unveils agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
At the opening of the international peace conference, which gathered under his leadership in Annapolis, Maryland, on Tuesday, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He further stated that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start negotiations immediately in order to find a final settlement of the 60-year-old disputes between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do everything he could to help them conclude a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, the Palestinians must destroy the terrorist infrastructures and Israel must stop its colonization work, Bush said, reminding the two parties of their commitments to the roadmap for peace that they had agreed to in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian authorities under Abbas ultimately aim for a peace treaty to clarify all open issues without exception, and including the key issues.
This designation encompasses the three major issues that the disputes between Israelis and Palestinians mainly revolve around: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem, and the fate of the Arab refugees who were expelled from their homeland, which lies in the present state of Israel, as a result of the 1948 conflict.
After the American president took the floor, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly and provide a settlement for all issues, including Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
When Olmert took the floor, he pledged that the forthcoming ceasefire negotiations would be conducted directly and without interruption, and that he would endeavour to end them before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for implementing his vision of two states, a Palestinian and an Israeli coexisting, for the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has disclosed that it has received assurances from Bush in this sense before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a great success for Washington, has launched a plan adopted by all Arab countries to offer Israel peace in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis is a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central points of view, says the Saudi Arabian prince in his interview with the Saudi-funded Arabic-language daily.
