Tension is increasing in Pakistan
On Monday, Pakistani police struck down the first demonstrations since the state of emergency was declared two days earlier by General Musharraf.
According to witness reports, in the town of Lahore in the east of the country, about 2,000 lawyers demonstrating against the measures taken within the framework of the emergency were injured by the tear gas grenades deployed by the police forces there.
They then threw stones with which they wounded the police officers.
At least 350 lawyers were temporarily arrested.
Similar scenarios existed in Karachi and Rawalpindi, where police attacked and injured lawyers.
Several were temporarily detained.
In Islamabad, lawyers from the Supreme Court have called for a general strike and announced demonstrations as a result of a wave of about 500 arrests of oppositionists, human rights advocates and lawyers during the weekend.
Monday morning, the streets leading to the Supreme Court had been closed to prevent the assembly.
Further demonstrations would have taken place in Multan (center) and Peshawar (northeast).
The lawyers movement on Monday received the support of the religious parties united in the powerful Muttahida Majlis-e-Amal alliance, whose president called on the population to send flowers to the judges who opposed the emergency and to those who took an oath before Musharraf.
Musharraf's promise no longer applies
The Supreme Court of Pakistan is directly affected by the special measure announced on Saturday evening.
He had to take a stand on the legality of President Musharraf’s re-election in a direct election on October 6.
The president of the Court, Iftikhar Mohammed Chaudhry, was removed from office and replaced.
Everything we represent is illegal, anti-constitutional, and contrary to Supreme Court decisions, the magistrate told The News.
Pervez Musharraf’s pledge to give command of the army and become a civilian president has not been valid since the invocation of the emergency, Tariq Azeem, vice-minister of information, said on Monday.
He was expected to hand over his military uniform until November 15, the date of his first term as president.
The Deputy Minister of Information has also confirmed that the January elections could be postponed.
In addition, the Pakistani government denied the persistent rumors in the country that President Musharraf had been assigned a place of residence by his deputy army leader.
