Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his comrades from the International Space Station (ISS) crew will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a defective solar collector, which is indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools crafted by the astronauts to perform the repair.
The problem occurred on Wednesday when the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that is expected to soon take up European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module labs.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to implement a 17.5-ton solar panel power generation module that was already on the ISS to bring it into its final position.
After it had shifted, the crew began to restructure the solar panels of the module, whose span is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors that can be folded up like accordions was damaged by a clamped cable on a length of about one meter.
Restructuring was stopped so as not to damage the collector any more.
The astronauts, who were originally to leave the space shuttle Discovery for a check-up and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around at the end of the 30-meter-long remote-controlled arm of the space shuttle attached to the station to perform the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skillful, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
So the 46-year-old learned doctor was selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After carefully examining the damage, he cut through the faulty cable and fixed some kind of rails to the damaged site.
He was supported by a second spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey racket, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar panels that generate several hundred volts, had the astronauts on board the station devised and crafted.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the collector to fully unfold before counting his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today’s seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery to start their return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
