Originally, the group had planned a first delivery of the A400M to the French army in October 2009.
Choosing the status quo
On Sunday, the counting of the urns will not be exciting: the mass of Russians will opt for President Putin’s party, United Russia.
After a very closed election campaign, it confirms its pursuit of stability, even authoritarianism.
Three days before the parliamentary elections, Russian President Vladimir Putin sends a message on public channels to voters, which has already been recorded, but whose content is kept secret.
He does so in his capacity as the top candidate of the United Russia, the pro-Kremlin party, for which an overwhelming victory is announcing.
Yesterday, the president failed to see anything when he received the foreign ambassadors, and was content to deliver a new point of attack against the Western powers accused of interference – his favorite topic during the election campaign.
We know the price of a true democracy and hope for honest elections, extremely transparent and open, elections without fraud, he added.
From the point of view of the opposition, they have lost themselves.
It denounces an election campaign stained by oppression.
Communist leader Guennadi Ziouganov says there would never have been such dirty elections, not even in the time of Eltsin.
After suppressing last weekend’s demonstrations, former chess world champion Garry Kasparovder was sentenced to five days in prison for illicit demonstrations, according to his lawyer.
The Russians have preserved the mentality of Homo Sovieticus
After these parliamentary elections without tension, two far-reaching questions arise:
Who will succeed Putin as President?
The official newspaper announced yesterday the date of the first round of presidential elections, 2 March 2008; the candidates have until 23 December to make themselves known.
Since he was re-elected in 2000 and re-elected in 2004, Vladimir Putin cannot stand for a third consecutive mandate.
And now there is no successor.
What role will Putin play after March?
Prime Minister?
President of the parliamentary majority and the almighty party United Russia, which will elect the government and president?
Whatever it will be, in the parliamentary elections or in the presidential elections, the previous power will triumph.
This is tradition.
The Russians have preserved the mentality of Homo Sovieticus, they are not masters of their fate, says the sociologist Lev Goudkov, director of the Independent Center Levada.
Historian Nikolai Kopossov of the State University of St. Petersburg goes even further back: bourgeois society has developed very slowly in this country, which was Christianized five centuries after Europe; the famous spirit of community has delayed the development of individuality.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, Putin reconnected with the model of a paternalistic state, which was fully accepted by the population, all the more so as this new paternalism was not followed by terror but by a certain economic prosperity, says Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
Today, the Russians voluntarily renounce the personal responsibility that they have shown for a short time after the collapse of the USSR.
Why consider it for a long time?
This phenomenon affects all layers of society, including the business world.
And the administrative elite knows how to maintain the status quo: 65 governors (out of 85 Russian regional leaders) lead the local election lists of the United Russia.
The new liberties coming from the West are often synonymous with chaos, as they were in the 1990s.
The general public prefers stability.
In this sense, the Russians will not vote for the extremist parties.
Conclusion of Tamara Tcherednichenko, a 54-year-old professor: Why long to consider?
Those in power are not so bad, why replace them?
A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed on a total length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen, could not be viewed until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, i.e. individually and by name, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
The eleven states entrusted with managing them, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to make them accessible to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
delicate information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will enable them to conduct research, especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of concentration camps, and the health status of forced labourers, explains Reto Meistern, head of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public, due to the delicate nature of certain information.
Such as the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmate lists of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labour, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen process tens of thousands of personal inquiries.
Nonetheless, some of the scientific community shows limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, Pr. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, explained in 2006.
The EU and India want to reach a free trade agreement in 2008.
Mutual trade between India and Europe is currently reaching 60 billion euros per year.
The EU is India’s main trading partner and accounts for 18% of its foreign trade.
European Trade Minister Peter Mandelson and his Indian counterpart, Kamal Nath, said that the European Union and India hope to sign a free trade agreement in 2008.
The EU Foreign Ministers gave the European Commission the green light to open negotiations last April with a view to signing free trade agreements (ALE) with India, South Korea and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
The EU is India’s first trading partner, accounting for 18% of its foreign trade.
The EU is also its first foreign investor, but according to the figures of the European Commission, India is only the ninth trading partner of the EU.
A free trade pact will drive the two economies forward enormously and India would improve its access to a market of 450 million wealthy Europeans, Peter Mandelson confirmed.
Europe constitutes the first or second market for the ten most frequently exported products from India, the European Commissioner continued. The Asian and European giants annually exchange goods worth 47 billion euros and services worth 10 billion euros, had this week Daniéle Smadja, chairman of the delegation of the European Commission in New Delhi, declared, and regretted that the mutual trade has not yet reached its potential at the European Commission.
(Source AFP)
The Bank of England notes the concern and offers 10 billion pounds for five weeks
The Bank of England on Thursday expressed concern about curbing the currently recurring concern about credit terms, announcing an offer of ten billion pounds at a base rate of 5.75% for five weeks, an offer of unusual duration.
In order to alleviate the fears that financial market conditions will be particularly harsh at the end of the year, and to give banks greater certainty about the way in which they should organize their liquidity positions during this period, the Bank intends to offer a significant portion of its savings deposits during the maintenance phase, which begins on 6 December, in the form of an open-market operation.
The bank further states that this way, on December 6th, by 12.15 GMT, 10 billion pounds (14 billion euros) will be put into circulation, at the property tax rate and only until January 10.
This seems to be the first time that BoE has put liquidity into circulation for five weeks in an open-market operation.
This usually happens for a week.
The BoE adds in its notice that it is prepared to take further action to receive the interest rates of interbank loans with their basic interest rate, which vary from day to day.
The interbank interest rate, which varies from day to day, was 5.829% on Wednesday.
The three-month interest rate has narrowed to 6.6%, slightly higher since September 18.
Since the beginning of the financial crisis this summer, the sums circulated by the Bank of England have been coupled with penalties that had prevented the banks from using them.
According to certain rumours, reinforced by the development of the pound price as opposed to the euro, many preferred to sign for the sums brought into circulation by the European Central Bank at more advantageous interest rates and with safer discretion.
