Is the stock market facing a year-end rally? Disagreement among experts due to the US mortgage crisis
With just under five weeks until the end of the year on the stock market, investors are already rubbing their hands in view of the upcoming final year rally.
Nevertheless, the experts can not make sure predictions in this regard.
Banif believes that purely statistically, the month of December on the stock market usually goes hand in hand with a positive market development
Nevertheless, it is not advisable to make forecasts on a short-term basis and only on the basis of statistics, especially if serious tensions determine the current market situation.
Although other experts do not approve of such a strong price increase in the last few weeks of the year, they nevertheless note that the stock market price is determined by the given liquidity of the market and the market participants, who invest mainly in pension funds due to the lack of secure equity funds, which is heavily affected by the upward trend towards high-yield assets.
As a result, according to these experts, the stock market will be more likely to show a rather lateral price trend influenced by market fluctuations, mainly because we are not yet able to estimate the extent of the potential fall in the interest rate of the US Federal Reserve, an uncertainty that is mainly due to the rising price of crude oil and the risk of the rise in inflation.
Javier Barrio, Head of Sales at BPI in Spain, agrees that it is a daring time to announce an upcoming market rally.
The chances are not very good, the expert assures.
The Spanish stock index Ibex has already lost a value of 4% since its peak on 8 November of 15,945.7 points.
But not all experts share the same negative opinion.
According to Juan Solana, an analyst at Intermoney, the Ibex 35 could successfully close the year by nearly 16,000 points as a result of the restructuring of mutual funds and the traditional pension fund subsidy at this time every year.
Nevertheless, the expert points out that this year things could develop slightly differently, especially due to the end-of-year rally already taking place in the second week of December, and thus immediately after the day of the bridge to the day of the Constitution.
According to the analyst, price fluctuations would not affect market trends.
According to Federico Olucha, analyst at Bank Inversis, the market situation is at an almost technical level, which could soon result in a deviation from index values whose extent depends on the consequences of the U.S. mortgage market crisis.
The analyst trusts that these will be positive.
When it comes to selecting the values to push the Ibex to new heights, analysts agree.
Solana of Intermoney affirms that this year's big values are at their turn.
Among the value winners, the expert would include the two major banks and some real estate companies, as the electricity sector will be too expensive at some point in time.
Meanwhile, Federico Olucha from Bank Inversis assures that the increases will be associated with the banking and industrial sectors.
If the rally actually happens, the real estate companies will benefit from it.
ACS has been on a catch-up course in recent months and we hope other real estate companies like Ferrovial and FCC will follow the same path, according to the expert.
With regard to the increased consumption behavior during the Christmas days, periodic consumption will determine market events in the last half of the year.
On the other hand, the expert believes that the technologies will also achieve positive sales results, even if they are only in small numbers on the Spanish market.
Five times in seven years
In the last seven years, December has only seen two declines in price.
When the technology bubble burst at the end of 2003, this led the stock market out of its crisis and at the same time initiated the last real year rally so far.
This year, in which the Ibex 35 picked up 28.17 percentage points, December showed a 6.68% increase in price.
Whether 2008 will be the fifth year in a row (the Ibex is up 8.36% since January) and also a final year rally will show.
Popular will have its 200 credit institutions open 12 hours a day from Monday to Friday.
Popular has decided to modernize a large part of its stores.
A total of 200 of these are located in the strongest economic regions in Spain.
For the institute, which operates under the brand name Popular Max, these branches represent a major milestone.
But also for the rest of the Spanish institutes, as Popular is the first banking group to dare to extend the opening hours of its branches on weekdays to 20.30h and start on Saturdays from 10h to 20.30h.
The banking group BBVA, which also repeatedly announced the extension of its opening hours in the branches, has not yet made a definitive decision.
The bank’s current negotiations with the trade unions seem to aim for an agreement in which 75% of all branches will be closed on Saturday and open on a weekday afternoon, albeit not for customers.
Whether other banks join the new initiative, which adapts to opening hours, will depend on the experience of Popular Bank.
And that is precisely the intention that Popular pursues with their project.
The aim is to extend the opening hours of those stores that, due to their location, can capture the commercial customers of independent, small and medium-sized companies, but also those of large department stores.
The bank wants to open the new 200 branches over the next 18 months, as these are not new but changed opening hours.
To this end, the bank will redesign the premises of those branches that are already in business zones, while at the same time aligning them with the individual customer profile of the different zones.
In this way, the extension of the opening hours is combined with a new interior design of the stores, which is characterized by a more up-to-date, colourful design.
The bank’s representative, Angel Rivera, assures that the restructuring did not require major investments, but was accompanied by an increased recruitment, as a branch no longer needed six, but eight or nine employees.
The branches, which will even be equipped with additional premises for SMEs, will not sell financial products.
A positive experience for the group
Popular has already tested his concept at nine stores in Madrid.
And the experience was positive, says Angel Rivero.
The branches of the streets Bravo Murillo, O’Donell and Gran V’a have been chosen for what seems to have been a wise decision.
Popular currently manages about 2,500 branches.
And another 60 who operate under the name Mundocredit. These are specialized in immigrants and also have extended opening hours, even on Sundays and holidays.
In these stores of PopularMax, the model of BBVA is not used, as most of them will instead offer a wide range of non-financial services for sale.
We do not want to be a competitor for our customers, Rivero explains.
