Congress approved the MIFID directive, which came into force on November 1.
In parallel with the parliamentary drafting, which ended its session today with the Senate congressional decision on the additional/amendments related to the project, the government published the provisions resulting from the new law with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the congress and senate members, who had in their negotiations and votes pursued the goal of establishing the best possible regulation that ensures the security of investors and regulates the individual entrepreneurial activities in order to guarantee a generally efficient market.
In addition to modernising the financial markets, the MIFID, which re-defines the securities services regulation, pursues an improvement in investor protection, the increase in the control entitlement of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and the promotion of cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive enables financial advice to be provided to both specialized firms and to natural or legal persons, and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS), the advisory firms that partner with the investment and brokerage firms of securities.
In addition, it expands the number of financial transaction execution systems, adding to the regulated circulation markets the multilateral securities trading systems and the systems for internationalising trade orders, which would eventually compete with the current economic operators.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose the focus of their company profile, the confrontation and the forms of dealing with risks in the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the CNMV’s control task.
The Congressional Economic Commission proposed further changes in retrospect, with the decision that titled bonds must now be considered as complex funds for the investor due to their high degree of risk has been confirmed by the U.S. mortgage and banking crisis.
In addition, the entry into force of the Directive on the legal limitation of the fields of work of qualified economists was used; 30 years after the 1977 regulation, which restricted the areas of work reserved for economists, was adopted.
The Senate, in turn, established new positions in the financial sector, such as that of the business mediator, who works on a third-party account, does not require authorization on the part of the CNMV and can offer its services to commercialize products and attract customers simultaneously to multiple investment companies.
The harmonised index of consumer prices (CPI) rose by five tenths in November and now stands at 4.1%.
The indicator used by Eurostat to assess the inflation rate within the European Union provides the average price trend in Spain in November.
Its publication complies with the principles of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB), which aim to compare location and quality with US products by publishing the data.
The forecast for the indicator can be created prematurely by applying the same procedure as for the harmonised consumer price index, but at the same time using various other statistical modelling methods to estimate the information not available at the time of calculation.
However, the Spanish Statistical Office (INE) warned that the pre-determined indicator would only serve as a guideline and therefore would not be in line with the final result announced on 14 December.
