New fears about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute swells between Ukraine and Russia, which increases the risk of Russian fuel exports to Western Europe being compromised.
Most of Russia’s natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) are led by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is closely monitored.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price it has to pay for natural gas, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent quarrel between Kiev and Moscow is happening at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian, state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be charged more, as the group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks,” Ukraine’s economic minister Anatoli Kinakh told Reuters.
“The changing prices of natural gas should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine.”
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom cut deliveries to Ukraine.
This resulted in a fall in exports to Western Europe, which pushed prices drastically upwards.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas deposits in the world, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the checks on criminal records for workers from outside Europe, a member of the control body said.
The recommendation of chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in connection with the attack at Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish state health service has no exact idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important checks were performed correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at the Old Bailey in October and was charged in connection with the alleged car bombing in the UK.
The State Health Service is expected to carry out checks prior to hiring foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the agency does not have the authority to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should adopt guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these checks in some personnel records, they were not routinely carried out," the report noted.
Black said Scottish health authorities would highly follow their investigative guidelines prior to hiring, but added: “Our report highlights areas where the system can be improved to ensure accurate information is available on the number of foreign health care workers.”
BMA Scotland Chairman Dr. Peter Terry said it was “extremely unlikely” that investigations ahead of hiring potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
“The report states that current NHS Scotland pre-employment tests are working well and it’s not clear what added value the recommendations will deliver,” he said.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the board members had trouble identifying those employees who were on leave indefinitely.
The investigation also found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian were predominantly observed.
These include passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
Nicola Sturgeon, Secretary of Health, said: "It was my concern to carry out this work in the face of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with health authorities, would take into account the recommendations of the report and ensure that the best practices would be reflected in updated guidelines on pre-employment checks by all employees, including those from abroad, whose publication is scheduled for next month.
