The climate on Venus could reveal a glimpse of the future of Earth
Venus may have been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft orbiting an orbit show that the planet resembles an averted twin of the Earth even more than previously was aware.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But due to the unrestrained carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation, and a slower rotational rate, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is deprived of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-strong winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which has been investigating the plant for a year, provide a sobering glimpse of how the Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at Oxford University, one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said, “It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar.”
“Our new data allows us to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment.”
