The pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall in; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly slippery.
No noble titles seem to be sold, no Parisian politician pays hotel bills, no extramarital toes have been sucked.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has disguised donations to the British ruling Labour Party over more than 650,000 pounds (1.3 million dollars) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something without which the contested Gordon Brown would have done well.
When, two months ago, the Prime Minister had withdrawn from the call for an election, in a stupid way offensive to the intelligence of the British, claiming that opinion polls had not affected this decision, there was hope that he would provide a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly keen representative leader of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once feared Brown has evolved from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The awkward rescue of Northern Rock, a battered bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change tax laws have raised corporate associations against the government.
The tax-administrative loss of personal data of 25 million people showed unimaginable administrative purgatory.
A trio of retired generals started an uprising in the upper house in protest against cuts in military spending: being Minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the many donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s Secretary General (and her former Executive Director) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably heading for resignation.
Yet governments can reach a turning point after which they find it impossible to govern.
People may not trust or trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it becomes clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn’t even need to be there for long, this postponement is over: the public service is starting to leak; the cabinet ministers are starting to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown’s position is particularly difficult because unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would like to deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-in-chief.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction documents, for example, are related to decisions that Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's mishaps -- as with the long "money for noble titles" investigation of political party funding -- voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's location isn't quite as bad as it looks
The wrongdoing is not as horrible as the conservatives describe it.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died or was completely tricked.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is delivering what Brown’s, of course, Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new guild of political donations is a good example.
The garboeske Abraham, who compares his donations with his charitable gifts, says he does not wish public recognition for his benevolence.
It may be so, but it was not up to him to decide.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he would have known about Abraham’s agreement, but not that it is illegal, will naturally have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s main fundraiser, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far, Brown hasn’t been involved: there’s nothing to suggest he knew about these confusions, even though most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He has quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he diluted this determination by grabbing a known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to the full measure, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "learnings to be drawn from this" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it is a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things Mr Brown needs to do, such as find a permanent chairman for the Independent Committee on Public Standards, which has been unoccupied for six months, and move forward with a major reform of political party funding.
This would require the hardliners of the Labour Party to cooperate with the conservatives and possibly give up the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party mate like Mr. Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to regain voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through unquestionable righteousness and solid competence.
