Venus is the Earth's hellish twin
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has discovered lightnings in the atmosphere and wind swirls on the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected it is flashing on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: The lightnings on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "original soup theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms in the ocean are said to have stimulated reactions that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees Celsius.
"Venus may be the devil's twin of the Earth, but she's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken such a completely different development is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, since since the early 1990s no probe was specifically on the way to exploring this planet.
The latest research, which is now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscores the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the similarities of our neighboring planet to Earth are greater than initially assumed," the Esa said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud swirl at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents on the earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits around the sun in just under 225 days.
But he turns much slower about himself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated that remained on Earth in oceans, but on which Venus was lost in space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on Earth in carbonate rocks, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
