Those who combine the terms Sweden and wooden box think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Isn't it?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden throw dark shadows on Warhol's works directory.
A large part of the ninety-four "Stockholm-type" Brillo boxes listed there are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes of 1968 a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now comes to a sobering result: The six "Brillo boxes" that the former museum director Pontus Hultén donated to the Moderna Museet in 1995 as a gift to the around one hundred of the "Brillo's" are probably copies.
The prehistory is nestled, a confusing combination of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the soap powder "Brillo" cardboard boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol’s consent, featured hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these were not (for cost reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cartonage factory.
They were not works of art, but their role models, they were mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of around fifteen boxes, which at that time were authorized as original Andy Warhol Brillo boxes with the designation "Type Stockholm" and rightly entered into the art and auction history.
Some of them made more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that around a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief conservator at Moderna Museet, has also examined three privately owned Brillo boxes, two of which were produced in Stockholm in 1968: their press plates were first primed and sanded, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressing plate with a painting roll without a primer - moreover, it is not oil paint but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," said Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet, "if the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced to pursue the “severe accusations” that are being raised in matters of soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, they have remained in relentless silence.
Rebellious soldiers in Manila give up
Rebellious soldiers in the Philippines have given up entrenched in a hotel in Manila and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
He cannot be held responsible for bloodshed, the leader Antonio Trillanes, who accused the president of corruption and election fraud, told reporters in the hotel.
Governmentally loyal soldiers had stormed the hotel previously under tear gas use.
The approximately two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
Around half of them were tried on Thursday for a failed coup attempt in 2003, including Trillane.
He took advantage of the trial to suddenly settle down with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police officers, who were supposed to guard him, apparently ran over to him and joined his mutiny.
They invaded the Peninsula hotel and demanded the overthrow of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal government forces blocked the district around the noble hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National security adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have enough," Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the elite unit of the Scout Rangers, said other army units wanted to join the march soon.
Government critics had called for large demonstrations against the president on Friday.
Their government has been overshadowed by corruption allegations for months.
Manila's financial district was already the main venue for the attempted mutiny of about 200 military personnel against Arroyo in 2003.
The uprising failed after nearly 24 hours because the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
United Internet becomes major shareholder in Versatel
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20 percent in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, as the company announced on Wednesday evening.
You now hold 20.05 percent of the share capital.
A takeover had previously been speculated.
The option is open to increase the share of sates.
The move is intended to advance the consolidation of the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Earlier on Wednesday, presumptions had already arisen about an entry, after Berenberg Bank has increased its stake in the Düsseldorf network operator by a further 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
The money house considers the shares to be only a third party, it said in the financial market.
The previous day, United Internet had already participated in the mobile company Drillisch with just under 10 percent.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch has placed 17.4 million new shares worth 106.4 million euros.
United Internet has purchased 5.15 million shares for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have started discussions about marketing cooperations for DSL and mobile products.
“We are strengthening our partnership,” said a United Internet spokesman.
The two companies have established the joint venture MSP to acquire the competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to satisfy themselves with a good ten percent stake in Freenet and do not make use of their right to take over an additional 18.49 percent stake in Freenet, United Internet said on Thursday.
However, the two companies kept all options open, in particular to further increase their participation in Freenet AG, it said.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet about a strategic partnership had ended in mid-November.
The poker around Freenet, which has been going on for months and is still difficult to see, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
Freenet had 2.9 million mobile contract customers and 1.27 million DSL and full line customers by the end of the third quarter.
The holding of United Internet and Drillisch held 6.01 percent of the freenet shares so far.
It has now been agreed that Drillisch will bring in another 4%.
The right to buy the 18.49 percent from the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
